\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/modlgal.top_slope}{Top slope}}
\begin{definition}\label{modlgal.top_slope}
\uses{lf,lf.slopes,lf.top_slope,modlgal,modlgal.splitting_field,nf.local_algebra}
Given a \hyperref[modlgal]{mod-$\ell$ Galois representation} $\rho$, let $K$ be its  \hyperref[modlgal.splitting_field]{splitting field}.  Then the \hyperref[nf.local_algebra]{local $\ell$-adic algebra} $K\otimes\mathbb{\Q}_{\ell}$ is isomorphic to a product of \hyperref[lf]{$\ell$-adic fields}.  The \textbf{top Artin slope} of the representation is the largest \hyperref[lf.slopes]{Artin slope} among these fields, which equals the \hyperref[lf.top_slope]{top Artin slope} for their compositum.

Note that a top slope of $0$ signifies that the field is unramified at $\ell$, and a top slope of $1$ indicates that it is ramified, but only tamely.  Otherwise the top slope is the largest \hyperref[lf.slopes]{wild slope}.
\end{definition}
